00:03:39.180 --> 00:03:43.260
So we start with these
first beginning steps.

00:03:43.260 --> 00:03:47.810
Number one, we want
to identify the needs

00:03:47.810 --> 00:03:49.290
and really understand
the problem.

00:03:49.290 --> 00:03:52.109
In our last class I gave
you a design challenge.

00:03:52.109 --> 00:03:54.150
So this is the first step,
identifying the needs.

00:03:54.150 --> 00:03:57.600
What is the problem we're
really trying to solve?

00:03:57.600 --> 00:03:59.800
And if we can get
underneath that

00:03:59.800 --> 00:04:04.750
we can design something in
a much more impactful way.

00:04:04.750 --> 00:04:09.010
So let's talk about this
interesting example here.

00:04:09.010 --> 00:04:14.090
I had a teacher as
an undergraduate

00:04:14.090 --> 00:04:18.910
who designed a toothbrush.

00:04:18.910 --> 00:04:20.329
Now, I'll show you a picture.

00:04:20.329 --> 00:04:23.410
This is Napoleon's toothbrush.

00:04:23.410 --> 00:04:26.200
Napoleon Bonaparte
used this toothbrush.

00:04:26.200 --> 00:04:28.460
A long time ago.

00:04:28.460 --> 00:04:31.400
If you bought a toothbrush
in the '60s or something,

00:04:31.400 --> 00:04:33.830
you'd buy a toothbrush
that looked like this.

00:04:33.830 --> 00:04:35.700
Does that look
familiar to people?

00:04:35.700 --> 00:04:37.762
Yeah, OK.

00:04:37.762 --> 00:04:39.720
He designed a toothbrush
that looked like this.

00:04:42.314 --> 00:04:43.980
That's his design,
the Reach toothbrush.

00:04:43.980 --> 00:04:45.990
Who's heard of the
Reach toothbrush?

00:04:45.990 --> 00:04:46.560
OK.

00:04:46.560 --> 00:04:47.540
And there are a lot
of different versions

00:04:47.540 --> 00:04:49.390
that they wound up
making over time.

00:04:49.390 --> 00:04:52.540
But that's the early
version of the toothbrush.

00:04:52.540 --> 00:04:55.020
People brush longer
and more thoroughly

00:04:55.020 --> 00:04:58.570
based on the design of
the toothbrush alone--

00:04:58.570 --> 00:05:00.060
with no instructions.

00:05:00.060 --> 00:05:02.980
Here's what happened.

00:05:02.980 --> 00:05:07.110
If you have a toothbrush and
it's a flat head toothbrush

00:05:07.110 --> 00:05:10.890
like the one we showed you
before here-- like that-- you

00:05:10.890 --> 00:05:14.450
hold it, you start brushing
your teeth like this.

00:05:14.450 --> 00:05:16.720
And you see people
can do this all day.

00:05:16.720 --> 00:05:19.100
They can watch a
sitcom with doing this

00:05:19.100 --> 00:05:21.070
to their front
teeth, no problem.

00:05:21.070 --> 00:05:21.980
Very comfortable.

00:05:21.980 --> 00:05:24.850
But if they need to brush
other parts of their mouth--

00:05:24.850 --> 00:05:28.400
and they do-- they do this.

00:05:28.400 --> 00:05:29.060
They take this.

00:05:29.060 --> 00:05:31.300
I'm going to represent
the bristles with my thumb

00:05:31.300 --> 00:05:33.510
and hold the handle like this.

00:05:33.510 --> 00:05:36.720
They brush their teeth
like this and then

00:05:36.720 --> 00:05:39.560
they get their rear molars
like this on the side.

00:05:39.560 --> 00:05:41.630
And they want to get
the upper rear molars

00:05:41.630 --> 00:05:43.660
on their sub dominant hand side.

00:05:43.660 --> 00:05:45.620
Which means they do this.

00:05:45.620 --> 00:05:46.250
Right?

00:05:46.250 --> 00:05:47.200
I'm writing, so I do this.

00:05:47.200 --> 00:05:49.533
So everyone, if you're a
righty, put your right hand up.

00:05:49.533 --> 00:05:51.242
If you're a lefty,
put your left hand up.

00:05:51.242 --> 00:05:53.450
Take your hand, make a fist
like that with your thumb

00:05:53.450 --> 00:05:58.100
out, curve your wrist over,
and bring it across like that.

00:05:58.100 --> 00:05:58.920
Now hold this.

00:05:58.920 --> 00:06:00.689
Is that comfortable?

00:06:00.689 --> 00:06:02.105
This is not a
comfortable position

00:06:02.105 --> 00:06:03.313
for your arm to be in, right?

00:06:03.313 --> 00:06:04.040
OK.

00:06:04.040 --> 00:06:05.700
So as a result, people do this.

00:06:05.700 --> 00:06:07.590
And if you watch them
do it, they do this

00:06:07.590 --> 00:06:09.700
and they go, ugh,
they get bored.

00:06:09.700 --> 00:06:12.340
And they stop brushing.

00:06:12.340 --> 00:06:13.310
That's not good.

00:06:13.310 --> 00:06:19.260
So this teacher, this professor
I had, to understand this,

00:06:19.260 --> 00:06:20.480
he did some studies.

00:06:20.480 --> 00:06:23.300
He had people stain
their teeth red.

00:06:23.300 --> 00:06:26.990
And then, with no mirror,
he said, brush your teeth.

00:06:26.990 --> 00:06:28.400
And people would brush it.

00:06:28.400 --> 00:06:29.941
And then he'd look
inside their mouth

00:06:29.941 --> 00:06:32.650
and see the red was all
of the front and all

00:06:32.650 --> 00:06:35.330
stuck in that part in the back.

00:06:35.330 --> 00:06:36.460
He said, that's no good.

00:06:36.460 --> 00:06:38.200
So he designed this thing.

00:06:38.200 --> 00:06:41.530
In fact, there's a ton of
innovations around this.

00:06:41.530 --> 00:06:42.520
Different handle.

00:06:42.520 --> 00:06:44.650
You see this side.

00:06:44.650 --> 00:06:47.110
Your thumb sits in that
groove really easily.

00:06:47.110 --> 00:06:50.870
In fact, you'll turn that
toothbrush 90 degrees

00:06:50.870 --> 00:06:52.690
and your thumb will
rest right there.

00:06:52.690 --> 00:06:54.250
You do it automatically.

00:06:54.250 --> 00:06:56.200
You'll do it
automatically like this.

00:06:56.200 --> 00:07:01.550
And this is thin over
here at an angle.

00:07:01.550 --> 00:07:03.582
So it doesn't pull your
cheek out like this .

00:07:03.582 --> 00:07:05.040
That's not very
comfortable, right?

00:07:05.040 --> 00:07:05.540
OK.

00:07:05.540 --> 00:07:06.287
So he did that.

00:07:06.287 --> 00:07:07.620
The head was shaped differently.

00:07:07.620 --> 00:07:09.860
Instead of doing a square
head, it's now tapered,

00:07:09.860 --> 00:07:11.750
the bristles are
shaped differently.

00:07:11.750 --> 00:07:14.330
So here's the question.

00:07:14.330 --> 00:07:17.430
What was the underlying
problem he was trying to solve?

00:07:21.090 --> 00:07:22.693
Kristen.

00:07:22.693 --> 00:07:24.577
AUDIENCE: The fact
that people weren't

00:07:24.577 --> 00:07:28.846
able to reach their
back teeth properly.

00:07:28.846 --> 00:07:30.220
BLADE KOTELLY:
That was a problem

00:07:30.220 --> 00:07:32.310
he was trying to solve but
it wasn't the underlying

00:07:32.310 --> 00:07:33.601
problem he was trying to solve.

00:07:36.246 --> 00:07:37.787
AUDIENCE: The fact
that people didn't

00:07:37.787 --> 00:07:38.960
want to brush their teeth.

00:07:38.960 --> 00:07:39.553
BLADE KOTELLY: The
fact that people

00:07:39.553 --> 00:07:40.928
didn't want to
brush their teeth.

00:07:40.928 --> 00:07:43.196
That's a problem that
he was helping with

00:07:43.196 --> 00:07:44.820
but that wasn't the
underlying problem.

00:07:47.540 --> 00:07:48.287
David.

00:07:48.287 --> 00:07:49.650
AUDIENCE: People with bad teeth.

00:07:49.650 --> 00:07:51.191
BLADE KOTELLY: People
have bad teeth?

00:07:51.191 --> 00:07:54.450
People with bad teeth--
not the underlying problem.

00:07:54.450 --> 00:07:54.995
[? Cosi? ?]

00:07:54.995 --> 00:07:56.578
AUDIENCE: The design
of the toothbrush

00:07:56.578 --> 00:07:57.662
hadn't changed in a while.

00:07:57.662 --> 00:07:59.453
BLADE KOTELLY: The
design of the toothbrush

00:07:59.453 --> 00:08:01.070
hadn't changed in
a while and we're

00:08:01.070 --> 00:08:02.990
getting closer now to
the underlying problem.

00:08:02.990 --> 00:08:06.060
Because we saw that Napoleon
had a toothbrush very

00:08:06.060 --> 00:08:09.100
similar to the toothbrush that
you could buy in the '60s.

00:08:09.100 --> 00:08:13.130
A small difference though, his
was they said silver-plated,

00:08:13.130 --> 00:08:15.470
I think.

00:08:15.470 --> 00:08:18.194
Anyone here own a
silver-plated toothbrush?

00:08:18.194 --> 00:08:19.540
OK.

00:08:19.540 --> 00:08:20.890
Yes, Dennis?

00:08:20.890 --> 00:08:22.810
AUDIENCE: The functionality
of the toothbrush?

00:08:22.810 --> 00:08:24.570
BLADE KOTELLY: The
functionality of the toothbrush.

00:08:24.570 --> 00:08:26.570
He definitely wanted to
change the functionality

00:08:26.570 --> 00:08:29.240
of the toothbrush but it
wasn't the underlying thing.

00:08:29.240 --> 00:08:29.913
Louis?

00:08:29.913 --> 00:08:33.350
AUDIENCE: Was it to simply
build a better toothbrush?

00:08:33.350 --> 00:08:36.189
BLADE KOTELLY: It was about
building a better toothbrush

00:08:36.189 --> 00:08:37.730
but that's not the
underlying reason.

00:08:40.429 --> 00:08:41.556
[? Shuni. ?]

00:08:41.556 --> 00:08:43.097
AUDIENCE: An
uncomfortable toothbrush

00:08:43.097 --> 00:08:45.799
was leading to poor
brushing habits.

00:08:45.799 --> 00:08:46.590
BLADE KOTELLY: Yes.

00:08:46.590 --> 00:08:48.215
But we're not getting
to the underlying

00:08:48.215 --> 00:08:51.150
reason, what made him do this.

00:08:51.150 --> 00:08:51.650
Emily.

00:08:51.650 --> 00:08:54.285
AUDIENCE: Was it low
toothbrush sales?

00:08:54.285 --> 00:08:55.660
BLADE KOTELLY:
Well, interesting.

00:08:55.660 --> 00:08:57.490
It wasn't-- we're
getting very close now--

00:08:57.490 --> 00:09:00.690
it wasn't low toothbrush
sales, per se.

00:09:00.690 --> 00:09:05.330
But by doing that
he did make somebody

00:09:05.330 --> 00:09:10.397
happy by increasing the
number of toothbrush sales.

00:09:10.397 --> 00:09:12.480
AUDIENCE: People have loads
of cavities back here?

00:09:12.480 --> 00:09:13.080
BLADE KOTELLY: Oh, cavities.

00:09:13.080 --> 00:09:14.371
No, we're getting further away.

00:09:14.371 --> 00:09:16.440
Cavities is cooler.

00:09:16.440 --> 00:09:18.806
Sales is warmer.

00:09:18.806 --> 00:09:19.305
Patrick.

00:09:19.305 --> 00:09:20.796
AUDIENCE: The ability
to increase the price

00:09:20.796 --> 00:09:22.280
on the toothbrushes
that are new?

00:09:22.280 --> 00:09:23.000
BLADE KOTELLY:
Increasing the price

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:24.270
of toothbrushes that are new.

00:09:24.270 --> 00:09:25.940
That's interesting.

00:09:25.940 --> 00:09:27.266
Kind of.

00:09:27.266 --> 00:09:27.820
Kind of.

00:09:27.820 --> 00:09:29.970
It's actually-- they
would have been happy

00:09:29.970 --> 00:09:34.234
if the toothbrushes
were the same price.

00:09:34.234 --> 00:09:35.650
AUDIENCE: I mean,
but you're like,

00:09:35.650 --> 00:09:38.130
trying to get people to
believe that it's worth

00:09:38.130 --> 00:09:39.370
what you're paying for.

00:09:39.370 --> 00:09:40.320
BLADE KOTELLY: Yes.

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:42.820
For what though?

00:09:42.820 --> 00:09:45.500
For this for that
particular toothbrush.

00:09:45.500 --> 00:09:46.850
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:09:46.850 --> 00:09:48.230
BLADE KOTELLY: Yes.

00:09:48.230 --> 00:09:51.050
It's a little bit-- it's a
shade of meaning difference.

00:09:51.050 --> 00:09:52.246
I think your close.

00:09:52.246 --> 00:09:54.030
AUDIENCE: To design
the best toothbrush?

00:09:54.030 --> 00:09:54.550
BLADE KOTELLY:
Well, he definitely

00:09:54.550 --> 00:09:56.050
wanted to design
the best toothbrush

00:09:56.050 --> 00:09:57.710
and he did at the time.

