you get residuals.

00:10:27.940 --> 00:10:30.240
Designers don't get residuals.

00:10:30.240 --> 00:10:30.965
They should.

00:10:30.965 --> 00:10:32.290
Definitely.

00:10:32.290 --> 00:10:32.790
Ben?

00:10:32.790 --> 00:10:34.114
AUDIENCE: Stakeholders?

00:10:34.114 --> 00:10:35.280
BLADE KOTELLY: Stakeholders.

00:10:35.280 --> 00:10:38.050
Yes, stakeholders, yes,
that's kind of close.

00:10:38.050 --> 00:10:39.450
A little bit too far back.

00:10:39.450 --> 00:10:42.618
But if you tell me
which stakeholders.

00:10:42.618 --> 00:10:43.550
AUDIENCE: Company.

00:10:43.550 --> 00:10:44.758
BLADE KOTELLY: Which company?

00:10:48.200 --> 00:10:50.630
AUDIENCE: Did he just not
like brushing his teeth?

00:10:50.630 --> 00:10:53.255
BLADE KOTELLY: I don't think he
cared about brushing his teeth.

00:10:53.255 --> 00:10:56.000
He was hired by a company
who said, hey, John.

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:57.080
We make blank.

00:10:57.080 --> 00:10:58.580
We want you to make
something that's

00:10:58.580 --> 00:11:01.050
going to sell a lot of blank.

00:11:01.050 --> 00:11:02.883
Can you fill in the blank?

00:11:02.883 --> 00:11:03.830
AUDIENCE: Toothpaste?

00:11:03.830 --> 00:11:04.620
BLADE KOTELLY: Not toothpaste.

00:11:04.620 --> 00:11:05.430
That's a great idea.

00:11:05.430 --> 00:11:06.263
It's not toothpaste.

00:11:11.140 --> 00:11:11.640
Emily.

00:11:11.640 --> 00:11:13.514
AUDIENCE: Is it the
nylon, like the bristles?

00:11:13.514 --> 00:11:14.710
BLADE KOTELLY: It is nylon.

00:11:14.710 --> 00:11:16.060
It is the bristles.

00:11:16.060 --> 00:11:18.230
Nylon is made by whom?

00:11:18.230 --> 00:11:19.480
DuPont.

00:11:19.480 --> 00:11:24.410
Nylon bristles started
coming out in, I think, 1936.

00:11:24.410 --> 00:11:27.320
And they, DuPont
loves to sell nylon.

00:11:27.320 --> 00:11:29.901
And they said, hey John, we
want to sell a lot of nylon.

00:11:29.901 --> 00:11:32.400
Can you do something that going
to help sell a lot of nylon?

00:11:35.600 --> 00:11:38.010
And they asked him to do this.

00:11:38.010 --> 00:11:41.990
So what he did is he looked
around the world and he said,

00:11:41.990 --> 00:11:44.436
what in the world
is made of nylon?

00:11:44.436 --> 00:11:46.270
It's a lot of research
just to figure out

00:11:46.270 --> 00:11:47.640
what's made of nylon.

00:11:47.640 --> 00:11:51.000
What hasn't been redesigned in
a long time that's made of nylon

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:52.620
that I could redesign?

00:11:52.620 --> 00:11:56.010
Hey, what hasn't been redesigned
in a long time, that's

00:11:56.010 --> 00:11:59.120
sold all over the
world, made of nylon,

00:11:59.120 --> 00:12:01.122
has existing manufacturing
capabilities,

00:12:01.122 --> 00:12:03.330
so it's really easy to make
a small modification that

00:12:03.330 --> 00:12:06.230
will sell a ton of nylon.

00:12:06.230 --> 00:12:06.730
Answer?

00:12:06.730 --> 00:12:08.310
Toothbrush.

00:12:08.310 --> 00:12:10.990
So he made a toothbrush
and he improved the design.

00:12:10.990 --> 00:12:13.530
And they made a tremendous
number of changes

00:12:13.530 --> 00:12:16.840
to the toothbrush in the
first design he made.

00:12:16.840 --> 00:12:19.110
And they kept releasing
them slowly over time.

00:12:19.110 --> 00:12:21.110
So people get used to it,
buy more toothbrushes,

00:12:21.110 --> 00:12:23.420
buy more nylon.

00:12:23.420 --> 00:12:24.720
Cool, right?

00:12:24.720 --> 00:12:26.842
So understand the
underlying reason.

00:12:26.842 --> 00:12:29.050
If you said, I want to sell--
if someone said to you,

00:12:29.050 --> 00:12:31.100
I want to sell a
lot of nylon, it's

00:12:31.100 --> 00:12:33.962
hard to figure out what to
do to sell a lot of nylon.

00:12:33.962 --> 00:12:35.880
And that was his approach.

00:12:35.880 --> 00:12:37.530
So what's the real problem here?

00:12:37.530 --> 00:12:38.360
Information phase.

00:12:38.360 --> 00:12:42.280
What in the world exists
that can inform us

00:12:42.280 --> 00:12:44.130
about this problem?

00:12:44.130 --> 00:12:48.710
So what kind of things might
you do to understand a problem?

00:12:52.472 --> 00:12:53.180
AUDIENCE: Google.

00:12:53.180 --> 00:12:53.930
BLADE KOTELLY: You
can use Google.

00:12:53.930 --> 00:12:54.922
Excellent.

00:12:54.922 --> 00:12:56.880
What else might you do
to understand a problem?

00:12:56.880 --> 00:12:59.520
AUDIENCE: Talk to people who
are suffering from the problem.

00:12:59.520 --> 00:13:00.020
BLADE KOTELLY: Talk to people.

00:13:00.020 --> 00:13:00.980
Do market research.

00:13:00.980 --> 00:13:02.060
Excellent.

00:13:02.060 --> 00:13:04.506
You might even look
at adjacent problems.

00:13:04.506 --> 00:13:06.130
Problems that are
not exactly the same.

00:13:06.130 --> 00:13:08.300
So if you're doing a
toothbrush redesign,

00:13:08.300 --> 00:13:09.800
what other kinds
of things might you

00:13:09.800 --> 00:13:12.410
look at to help
inform you about how

00:13:12.410 --> 00:13:13.660
to design a better toothbrush?

00:13:16.530 --> 00:13:17.213
Emily.

00:13:17.213 --> 00:13:18.060
AUDIENCE: Hair brush design.

00:13:18.060 --> 00:13:18.700
BLADE KOTELLY:
Hair brush design.

00:13:18.700 --> 00:13:19.650
Absolutely.

00:13:19.650 --> 00:13:21.002
Why?

00:13:21.002 --> 00:13:22.946
AUDIENCE: Might have
similar problems

00:13:22.946 --> 00:13:24.127
dealing with the product.

00:13:24.127 --> 00:13:25.210
BLADE KOTELLY: Absolutely.

00:13:25.210 --> 00:13:26.786
What else?

00:13:26.786 --> 00:13:28.084
AUDIENCE: Dental floss.

00:13:28.084 --> 00:13:29.250
BLADE KOTELLY: Dental floss.

00:13:29.250 --> 00:13:31.610
So you might figure out
what dental floss does well.

00:13:31.610 --> 00:13:33.194
In fact, there's a
dental floss device

00:13:33.194 --> 00:13:34.735
that looks kind of
like a toothbrush.

00:13:34.735 --> 00:13:35.610
It's got a handle.

00:13:35.610 --> 00:13:39.760
It's got a little small piece of
floss and you use it like this.

00:13:39.760 --> 00:13:41.700
So that's another way
of considering it.

00:13:41.700 --> 00:13:44.300
Excellent.

00:13:44.300 --> 00:13:45.350
Stakeholder phase.

00:13:45.350 --> 00:13:46.780
This is really important.

00:13:46.780 --> 00:13:48.530
What's wanted and who wants it?

00:13:51.830 --> 00:13:53.330
Just because you
can make it doesn't

00:13:53.330 --> 00:13:55.960
mean that people want it.

00:13:55.960 --> 00:13:58.060
Who knows what a VCR is?

00:13:58.060 --> 00:13:59.750
Great.

00:13:59.750 --> 00:14:03.120
This example won't work one day.

00:14:03.120 --> 00:14:03.620
OK.

00:14:03.620 --> 00:14:05.610
So here's the question.

00:14:05.610 --> 00:14:11.540
If I made a VCR, what functions
would it have to have.

00:14:11.540 --> 00:14:13.410
I'll start you off.

00:14:13.410 --> 00:14:15.485
Play.

00:14:15.485 --> 00:14:16.110
AUDIENCE: Stop.

00:14:16.110 --> 00:14:16.965
BLADE KOTELLY: Stop.

00:14:16.965 --> 00:14:17.380
AUDIENCE: Rewind.

00:14:17.380 --> 00:14:18.140
BLADE KOTELLY: Rewind.

00:14:18.140 --> 00:14:18.540
And?

00:14:18.540 --> 00:14:19.130
AUDIENCE: Fast forward.

00:14:19.130 --> 00:14:19.730
BLADE KOTELLY: Fast forward.

00:14:19.730 --> 00:14:20.230
What else?

00:14:20.230 --> 00:14:21.180
AUDIENCE: Eject.

00:14:21.180 --> 00:14:21.300
BLADE KOTELLY: Eject.

00:14:21.300 --> 00:14:22.942
That's great because
otherwise the tape

00:14:22.942 --> 00:14:24.480
is sitting stuck in there.

00:14:24.480 --> 00:14:27.060
Wow, it's an awesome
tape I keep using.

00:14:27.060 --> 00:14:29.816
I've watched "Tron" 145 times.

00:14:29.816 --> 00:14:31.047
AUDIENCE: Open.

00:14:31.047 --> 00:14:32.130
BLADE KOTELLY: What is it?

00:14:32.130 --> 00:14:33.087
AUDIENCE: Open.

00:14:33.087 --> 00:14:35.170
BLADE KOTELLY: Yes, so we
have an eject mechanism.

00:14:35.170 --> 00:14:36.094
Pause.

00:14:36.094 --> 00:14:36.760
AUDIENCE: Power.

00:14:36.760 --> 00:14:37.634
BLADE KOTELLY: Power.

00:14:37.634 --> 00:14:38.650
AUDIENCE: Record.

00:14:38.650 --> 00:14:39.846
BLADE KOTELLY: Power, yes.

00:14:39.846 --> 00:14:40.555
AUDIENCE: Record.

00:14:40.555 --> 00:14:41.471
BLADE KOTELLY: Record.

00:14:41.471 --> 00:14:42.145
That's great.

00:14:42.145 --> 00:14:44.103
AUDIENCE: Some of them
have the little displays

00:14:44.103 --> 00:14:44.959
with like the time.

00:14:44.959 --> 00:14:45.750
BLADE KOTELLY: Yes.

00:14:45.750 --> 00:14:48.165
I need a flashing 12:00.

00:14:48.165 --> 00:14:49.240
Let's do flash 12:00.

00:14:49.240 --> 00:14:49.740
OK.

00:14:49.740 --> 00:14:51.629
So, a time.

00:14:51.629 --> 00:14:53.170
Why do we have a
time display at all?

00:14:53.170 --> 00:14:55.808
Why was there ever a
time display on a VCR?

00:14:55.808 --> 00:14:57.519
AUDIENCE: So you know
long is the tape.

00:14:57.519 --> 00:14:58.560
BLADE KOTELLY: Well, yes.

00:14:58.560 --> 00:15:01.160
So we have some
sort of a method.

00:15:01.160 --> 00:15:02.596
That actually is separate.

00:15:02.596 --> 00:15:04.470
To position the tape,
I just use the counter.

00:15:04.470 --> 00:15:07.410
It might go up to a thousand
or something-- or more.

00:15:07.410 --> 00:15:09.500
The counter might tell me
a position of the tape.

00:15:09.500 --> 00:15:11.310
What'd the time tell me?

00:15:11.310 --> 00:15:12.500
Besides the time.

00:15:12.500 --> 00:15:14.050
AUDIENCE: How long
you've watched.

00:15:14.050 --> 00:15:15.290
BLADE KOTELLY: It could tell me
how long I've been watching it.

00:15:15.290 --> 00:15:16.745
It might allow me
to do something.

00:15:16.745 --> 00:15:17.870
AUDIENCE: Timed recordings.

00:15:17.870 --> 00:15:19.400
BLADE KOTELLY: Timed recordings.

00:15:19.400 --> 00:15:23.020
I could not have to be
home and I could set my VCR

00:15:23.020 --> 00:15:26.040
to record channel
four-- because back then

00:15:26.040 --> 00:15:29.780
we only had five
channels-- channel four

00:15:29.780 --> 00:15:33.190
and that would record
that at 5:00 PM

00:15:33.190 --> 00:15:34.920
when I didn't get
home till 7:00.

00:15:34.920 --> 00:15:36.310
Big deal.

00:15:36.310 --> 00:15:37.770
It was before DVRs.

00:15:37.770 --> 00:15:39.480
Amazing.

00:15:39.480 --> 00:15:40.050
What else?

00:15:43.940 --> 00:15:44.500
OK.

00:15:44.500 --> 00:15:45.375
I like that list too.

00:15:45.375 --> 00:15:50.330
So, let's suppose I made a VCR
and it had all these features

00:15:50.330 --> 00:15:54.710
on it but I took
away one feature.

00:15:54.710 --> 00:16:01.860
I took away the ability
for you to record.

00:16:01.860 --> 00:16:04.550
Show of hands, who thinks
that's still useful?

00:16:04.550 --> 00:16:06.540
Who thinks it's useless.

00:16:06.540 --> 00:16:07.040
OK.

00:16:07.040 --> 00:16:08.630
Why is it still useful?

00:16:08.630 --> 00:16:10.368
A VCR that cannot record.

00:16:10.368 --> 00:16:13.236
AUDIENCE: Because
that ability is

00:16:13.236 --> 00:16:17.060
pretty-- it's decoupled
from the other--

00:16:17.060 --> 00:16:19.317
from the other functions.

00:16:19.317 --> 00:16:21.900
BLADE KOTELLY: But why would I
want a VCR that doesn't record?

00:16:21.900 --> 00:16:23.469
AUDIENCE: So you
can watch movies?

00:16:23.469 --> 00:16:25.010
BLADE KOTELLY: So
I can watch movies.

00:16:25.010 --> 00:16:26.510
When would I want to
watch movies, but not

00:16:26.510 --> 00:16:27.551
be able to record things?

00:16:27.551 --> 00:16:28.780
AUDIENCE: When you rent them.

00:16:28.780 --> 00:16:30.113
BLADE KOTELLY: When I rent them.

00:16:30.113 --> 00:16:32.710
Or when I bring them to
a ski condo or something.

00:16:32.710 --> 00:16:35.400
I go to someone else's
place, we bring up videotapes

00:16:35.400 --> 00:16:37.150
and then people can
watch the video tapes.

00:16:37.150 --> 00:16:38.200
Right?

00:16:38.200 --> 00:16:38.760
Great.

00:16:38.760 --> 00:16:41.705
And what's the benefit of
not having that record head

00:16:41.705 --> 00:16:42.330
in the machine?

00:16:42.330 --> 00:16:44.630
Because it's a record
head and a playhead.

00:16:44.630 --> 00:16:47.195
AUDIENCE: It saves you a
lot of money manufacturing.

00:16:47.195 --> 00:16:49.570
BLADE KOTELLY: It saves you
a lot of money manufacturing.

00:16:49.570 --> 00:16:51.640
You can pass that savings
on to the consumer.

00:16:51.640 --> 00:16:54.200
Because these are two
different objects.

00:16:54.200 --> 00:16:55.530
OK.

00:16:55.530 --> 00:16:57.710
What if I took out,
instead of the record head,

00:16:57.710 --> 00:16:58.720
I took out the playhead.

00:16:58.720 --> 00:17:00.490
Who thinks that's useful?

00:17:00.490 --> 00:17:02.930
Who thinks it's useless?

00:17:02.930 --> 00:17:03.880
You're all wrong.

00:17:03.880 --> 00:17:05.713
No, it's you're all
right, in a certain way.

00:17:05.713 --> 00:17:07.579
Why do you think it's useless?

00:17:07.579 --> 00:17:09.280
I can't play videotape.

00:17:09.280 --> 00:17:10.069
Why is it useless?

00:17:10.069 --> 00:17:10.957
AUDIENCE: Because you
can record something.

00:17:10.957 --> 00:17:12.290
You can't watch it.

00:17:12.290 --> 00:17:14.164
BLADE KOTELLY: As soon
as I record something,

00:17:14.164 --> 00:17:15.150
I can't watch it.

00:17:15.150 --> 00:17:17.022
Kind of a weird
thing to do, right?

00:17:17.022 --> 00:17:19.230
Oh, I can't wait to watch
this thing when I get home.

00:17:19.230 --> 00:17:20.150
I've recorded it.

00:17:20.150 --> 00:17:20.720
Now what?

00:17:20.720 --> 00:17:23.150
I have no idea.

00:17:23.150 --> 00:17:24.200
But think of it this way.

00:17:27.520 --> 00:17:31.020
What if I had a
business and my business

00:17:31.020 --> 00:17:35.840
was a video
duplication business.

00:17:35.840 --> 00:17:40.001
You gave me one videotape and
I'd make thousands for you.

00:17:40.001 --> 00:17:42.450
You know at graduation
they shoot people

00:17:42.450 --> 00:17:43.330
when they walk down.

00:17:43.330 --> 00:17:47.200
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:47.200 --> 00:17:48.946
BLADE KOTELLY: With a camera.

00:17:48.946 --> 00:17:52.280
They shoot people when they walk
down and receive their diploma

00:17:52.280 --> 00:17:53.580
and they shake hands.

00:17:53.580 --> 00:17:56.770
So, they have you on videotape.

00:17:56.770 --> 00:17:58.900
And what if people want
to order videotapes?

00:17:58.900 --> 00:18:00.130
They want to duplicate them.

00:18:00.130 --> 00:18:03.420
Or back when you used to
buy videotapes, as a kid

00:18:03.420 --> 00:18:07.520
perhaps, you bought "Bambi"
and you wanted to get a copy.

00:18:07.520 --> 00:18:14.900
Well, there's some room where
there's a machine and it plays.

00:18:14.900 --> 00:18:20.310
And there are thousands
of machines that record.

00:18:20.310 --> 00:18:21.740
Thousands.

00:18:21.740 --> 00:18:23.030
They can record and rewind.

00:18:23.030 --> 00:18:24.840
They can do nothing else.

00:18:24.840 --> 00:18:26.550
They record and they rewind.

00:18:26.550 --> 00:18:28.460
And that's all they do.

00:18:28.460 --> 00:18:29.500
That's the whole thing.

00:18:29.500 --> 00:18:30.999
And so it's a lot
cheaper for people

00:18:30.999 --> 00:18:33.830
to buy thousands of those things
without the playhead or fast

00:18:33.830 --> 00:18:35.070
forward or anything else.

00:18:35.070 --> 00:18:37.720
You can really make it a
much less expensive product.

00:18:37.720 --> 00:18:39.886
So, just because you can
do it and you can put it on

00:18:39.886 --> 00:18:42.190
there doesn't mean you should.

00:18:42.190 --> 00:18:44.674
So, stakeholder phase is
also a little bit bigger.

00:18:44.674 --> 00:18:46.090
Who are the possible
stakeholders?

00:18:46.090 --> 00:18:47.280
We talked about this
a little bit before.

00:18:47.280 --> 00:18:49.970
I think Ben brought it up,
saying that the stakeholder can

00:18:49.970 --> 00:18:53.760
be shareholders or
they could be people

00:18:53.760 --> 00:18:58.480
who are related to the design
in some method, some aspect.

00:18:58.480 --> 00:19:03.095
Whether it's-- in this class.

00:19:03.095 --> 00:19:05.750
Let's take this
class, for example.

00:19:05.750 --> 00:19:11.020
Who are your stakeholders
in this class?

00:19:11.020 --> 00:19:12.806
Who's the primary stakeholder?

00:19:12.806 --> 00:19:13.800
AUDIENCE: Ourselves.

00:19:13.800 --> 00:19:14.620
BLADE KOTELLY: You.

00:19:14.620 --> 00:19:16.430
You're the primary stakeholder.

00:19:16.430 --> 00:19:17.630
Who's another stakeholder?

00:19:17.630 --> 00:19:18.412
AUDIENCE: Parents.

00:19:18.412 --> 00:19:19.370
BLADE KOTELLY: Parents.

00:19:19.370 --> 00:19:20.182
Why?

00:19:20.182 --> 00:19:21.896
AUDIENCE: Because
they're paying for it.

00:19:21.896 --> 00:19:23.770
BLADE KOTELLY: Because
they're paying for it.

00:19:23.770 --> 00:19:25.603
And they want to get
some value out of that.

00:19:25.603 --> 00:19:26.360
Who else?

00:19:26.360 --> 00:19:27.060
AUDIENCE: Staff.

00:19:27.060 --> 00:19:27.935
BLADE KOTELLY: Staff.

00:19:27.935 --> 00:19:28.490
Which staff?

00:19:28.490 --> 00:19:29.350
AUDIENCE: All of you guys.

00:19:29.350 --> 00:19:29.930
BLADE KOTELLY: All of us.

00:19:29.930 --> 00:19:31.141
So we're all stakeholders.

00:19:31.141 --> 00:19:33.390
AUDIENCE: You all want to
see this class be a success.

00:19:33.390 --> 00:19:33.550
BLADE KOTELLY: No.

00:19:33.550 --> 00:19:35.050
We want to see you be success.

00:19:35.050 --> 00:19:35.697
It's different.

00:19:35.697 --> 00:19:36.280
AUDIENCE: Aww.

00:19:36.280 --> 00:19:38.113
BLADE KOTELLY: I don't
care about the class.

00:19:38.113 --> 00:19:39.240
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:39.240 --> 00:19:40.230
It's true.

00:19:40.230 --> 00:19:41.220
AUDIENCE: I believe it.

00:19:41.220 --> 00:19:42.620
BLADE KOTELLY: The class
could be a massive failure,

00:19:42.620 --> 00:19:44.490
but if you're successful,
and we've helped

00:19:44.490 --> 00:19:46.390
you do that, then
we've been successful.

00:19:46.390 --> 00:19:48.015
That's our job, to
make you successful.

00:19:50.590 --> 00:19:52.973
What other stakeholders
do you have?

00:19:52.973 --> 00:19:53.779
AUDIENCE: MIT.

00:19:53.779 --> 00:19:54.570
BLADE KOTELLY: MIT.

00:19:54.570 --> 00:19:56.030
How's MIT a stakeholder?

00:19:56.030 --> 00:19:56.530
What?

00:19:56.530 --> 00:19:58.196
AUDIENCE: They're
putting us on their CW

00:19:58.196 --> 00:20:00.370
so they get more
attention to MIT--

00:20:00.370 --> 00:20:01.790
BLADE KOTELLY: Well, maybe so
they can get more attention

00:20:01.790 --> 00:20:03.370
or maybe so they
can share the ideas

00:20:03.370 --> 00:20:07.534
with people who can't be in
this room with all of you.

00:20:07.534 --> 00:20:09.450
So maybe there are two
different stakeholders.

00:20:09.450 --> 00:20:11.450
Maybe there's people that
want to get money from

00:20:11.450 --> 00:20:13.260
and say, look at
this cool class!

00:20:13.260 --> 00:20:14.630
I hope they think it's cool.

00:20:14.630 --> 00:20:16.340
Or maybe there are
people who say,

00:20:16.340 --> 00:20:18.090
I really wanted to
hear about that lecture

00:20:18.090 --> 00:20:20.420
that I can't get to.

00:20:20.420 --> 00:20:22.610
John's brother can't get
to this lecture today.

00:20:22.610 --> 00:20:23.990
Wanted to.

00:20:23.990 --> 00:20:25.050
Can't do it.

00:20:25.050 --> 00:20:27.196
So he's a stakeholder as
well of the recording.

00:20:27.196 --> 00:20:28.570
So lots of
stakeholders and we'll

00:20:28.570 --> 00:20:32.030
be discussing this next class.

00:20:32.030 --> 00:20:33.850
Now we do
planning/operational research.

00:20:33.850 --> 00:20:34.710
What's realistic?

00:20:34.710 --> 00:20:35.640
What limits us?

00:20:35.640 --> 00:20:38.250
If we want to make
something, what limits

00:20:38.250 --> 00:20:41.570
do we have whenever
we make something?

00:20:41.570 --> 00:20:42.430
AUDIENCE: Cost.

00:20:42.430 --> 00:20:43.010
BLADE KOTELLY: Cost.

00:20:43.010 --> 00:20:43.509
Sure.

00:20:43.509 --> 00:20:46.795
What do you mean by cost?

00:20:46.795 --> 00:20:48.822
AUDIENCE: The cost
of manufacturing.

00:20:48.822 --> 00:20:50.530
BLADE KOTELLY: The
cost of manufacturing.

00:20:50.530 --> 00:20:51.614
What about software?

00:20:51.614 --> 00:20:53.530
Does it cost anything
to manufacture software?

00:20:53.530 --> 00:20:54.230
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:20:54.230 --> 00:20:55.794
BLADE KOTELLY:
What does it cost?

00:20:55.794 --> 00:20:57.240
AUDIENCE: Time.

00:20:57.240 --> 00:20:59.110
BLADE KOTELLY: For
the-- well, yes.

00:20:59.110 --> 00:21:01.780
Let's call that the design
development portion.

00:21:01.780 --> 00:21:03.401
But how about the
manufacturing of it?

00:21:03.401 --> 00:21:04.900
Because if I
manufacture toothbrush,

00:21:04.900 --> 00:21:06.235
I've designed and
developed it and now I

00:21:06.235 --> 00:21:07.530
could have machines
that are stamping out

00:21:07.530 --> 00:21:09.200
toothbrushes and putting
bristles all on stuff.

00:21:09.200 --> 00:21:10.110
How about software?

00:21:10.110 --> 00:21:11.530
Any cost of software?

00:21:11.530 --> 00:21:13.830
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:21:13.830 --> 00:21:14.880
A lot less.

00:21:14.880 --> 00:21:15.880
There is a cost, though.

00:21:15.880 --> 00:21:18.046
Because I gotta pay somebody
to host it and somebody

00:21:18.046 --> 00:21:19.970
to-- every time you
download software,

00:21:19.970 --> 00:21:22.580
it costs a little bit of money
and that begins to add up.

00:21:22.580 --> 00:21:23.394
So yes.

00:21:23.394 --> 00:21:24.707
AUDIENCE: Cost of memory--

00:21:24.707 --> 00:21:25.790
BLADE KOTELLY: Absolutely.

00:21:25.790 --> 00:21:26.290
Yes.

00:21:26.290 --> 00:21:28.900
So there are costs
involved that can limit us.

00:21:28.900 --> 00:21:30.552
What else?

00:21:30.552 --> 00:21:31.460
AUDIENCE: Time.

00:21:31.460 --> 00:21:32.520
BLADE KOTELLY: Time.

00:21:32.520 --> 00:21:34.100
What kind of time?

00:21:34.100 --> 00:21:37.390
AUDIENCE: When you're in
the-- basically any stage,

00:21:37.390 --> 00:21:41.196
you have a certain amount
of time to get this done,

00:21:41.196 --> 00:21:43.004
so you've got deadlines to meet.

00:21:43.004 --> 00:21:44.550
Plus, if you're
paying people to work

00:21:44.550 --> 00:21:46.299
for you, the longer
they're working on it,

00:21:46.299 --> 00:21:48.479
the more that turns
into money later.

00:21:48.479 --> 00:21:49.270
BLADE KOTELLY: Yes.

00:21:49.270 --> 00:21:50.960
So there are lots
of costs involved.

00:21:50.960 --> 00:21:54.320
I'm sorry, lots of
time costs involved.

00:21:54.320 --> 00:21:56.200
So the time it
takes for something

00:21:56.200 --> 00:22:00.330
to be executed upon to the
time we have to execute it.

00:22:00.330 --> 00:22:02.920
In classes, you're
often limited by time.

00:22:02.920 --> 00:22:04.560
If you had an infinite
amount of time,

00:22:04.560 --> 00:22:08.180
you could learn the material
much more easily, probably.

00:22:08.180 --> 00:22:09.952
What else are we limited by?

00:22:09.952 --> 00:22:11.660
AUDIENCE: Finite amount
of raw materials.

00:22:11.660 --> 00:22:12.993
BLADE KOTELLY: Materials, right.

00:22:12.993 --> 00:22:17.380
And materials can come
in a lot of versions.

00:22:17.380 --> 00:22:20.470
Resources can be
physical resources,

00:22:20.470 --> 00:22:22.600
they can be people
resources, they

00:22:22.600 --> 00:22:26.080
can be environmental resources
that we have access to.

00:22:26.080 --> 00:22:27.538
Anything else?

00:22:27.538 --> 00:22:28.960
AUDIENCE: Technical
capabilities.

00:22:28.960 --> 00:22:29.410
BLADE KOTELLY: Abilities.

00:22:29.410 --> 00:22:30.340
Knowledge.

00:22:30.340 --> 00:22:32.160
We can be limited by knowledge.

00:22:32.160 --> 00:22:33.860
So we have a team--
a brilliant team.

00:22:33.860 --> 00:22:37.240
You're all brilliant people.

00:22:37.240 --> 00:22:39.430
Who here knows the
process of opening

00:22:39.430 --> 00:22:42.120
a restaurant that's successful?

00:22:42.120 --> 00:22:42.620
OK.

00:22:42.620 --> 00:22:45.760
So right now we're limited by
a certain level of knowledge.

00:22:45.760 --> 00:22:49.340
If we all decided to open a
successful restaurant tomorrow,

00:22:49.340 --> 00:22:51.550
but you are all
brilliant people,

00:22:51.550 --> 00:22:53.990
so maybe we could figure
it out very quickly.

00:22:53.990 --> 00:22:54.540
Maybe not.

00:22:54.540 --> 00:22:55.600
Maybe we'd find
someone who's already

00:22:55.600 --> 00:22:57.160
opened a successful
restaurant to let

00:22:57.160 --> 00:22:59.460
us know all the
things we should know

00:22:59.460 --> 00:23:02.360
and short circuit that amount
of failure time we have.

00:23:02.360 --> 00:23:03.030
OK.

00:23:03.030 --> 00:23:06.300
So, from there we go
into a hazard analysis.

00:23:06.300 --> 00:23:09.090
And we're thinking
about here, what's safe?

00:23:09.090 --> 00:23:10.820
Or what can go wrong?

00:23:10.820 --> 00:23:15.390
So in classical design, let's
say it's a baby's high chair.

00:23:15.390 --> 00:23:17.410
I might say, well,
if the baby can

00:23:17.410 --> 00:23:20.727
slip underneath the high
chair, that's not safe.

00:23:20.727 --> 00:23:22.310
So you gotta keep
that from happening.

00:23:22.310 --> 00:23:25.470
If I'm designing a
stock trading system,

00:23:25.470 --> 00:23:28.650
where online you get
to buy stock or maybe

00:23:28.650 --> 00:23:30.110
call over the phone.

00:23:30.110 --> 00:23:34.530
You say, buy 100 shares of
Microsoft at the market price.

00:23:34.530 --> 00:23:37.014
What could go wrong?

00:23:37.014 --> 00:23:37.680
AUDIENCE: Fraud.

00:23:37.680 --> 00:23:38.555
BLADE KOTELLY: Fraud.

00:23:38.555 --> 00:23:40.359
What kind of fraud?

00:23:40.359 --> 00:23:42.299
AUDIENCE: Someone
impersonates someone else

00:23:42.299 --> 00:23:44.340
BLADE KOTELLY: So we have
a security issue there.

00:23:44.340 --> 00:23:45.280
We don't know if you are you.

00:23:45.280 --> 00:23:46.484
What else can go wrong?

00:23:46.484 --> 00:23:49.448
AUDIENCE: In terms of how
you design the website

00:23:49.448 --> 00:23:50.930
or whatever else--
the interface--

00:23:50.930 --> 00:23:53.400
if it's really easy
to make mistakes.

00:23:53.400 --> 00:23:54.890
Say, an extra zero somewhere.

00:23:54.890 --> 00:23:55.960
BLADE KOTELLY: Yes.

00:23:55.960 --> 00:23:59.550
What if I put a number in
and I don't put the dots

00:23:59.550 --> 00:24:00.705
and I have two zeros.

00:24:03.612 --> 00:24:06.116
It's a bit more than
a rounding error.

00:24:06.116 --> 00:24:10.670
In fact, a friend of mine
just made a piece of software

00:24:10.670 --> 00:24:12.720
where you can pay-- you
walk into a restaurant

00:24:12.720 --> 00:24:14.720
and if they have the
software running,

00:24:14.720 --> 00:24:17.130
you can walk in to say,
I'm here at the restaurant.

00:24:17.130 --> 00:24:19.487
And then when you want to
leave, if a bunch of you

00:24:19.487 --> 00:24:21.320
are all eating together,
so we're all eating

00:24:21.320 --> 00:24:23.560
and we want to split
the bill differently,

00:24:23.560 --> 00:24:27.405
and he ordered something,
the very expensive caviar,

00:24:27.405 --> 00:24:29.280
and she ordered the very
expensive champagne,

00:24:29.280 --> 00:24:33.190
and she ordered the
very inexpensive fries,

00:24:33.190 --> 00:24:36.640
and she ordered the somewhat
moderately expensive chicken,

00:24:36.640 --> 00:24:38.224
and I didn't order anything.

00:24:38.224 --> 00:24:39.890
Well, we want to split
the bill somehow.

00:24:39.890 --> 00:24:42.150
Well, they make it
very easy to do it.

00:24:42.150 --> 00:24:46.952
But they were just testing it
in real life and for a server,

00:24:46.952 --> 00:24:49.160
the server came over said,
let me see how to do this.

00:24:49.160 --> 00:24:50.576
And he said, sure
let me show you.

00:24:50.576 --> 00:24:54.520
The server entered in the
numbers for how much we had.

00:24:54.520 --> 00:24:59.280
But it came out
to a huge number.

00:24:59.280 --> 00:25:00.130
Much more expensive.

00:25:00.130 --> 00:25:03.050
100 times more expensive.

00:25:03.050 --> 00:25:05.650
Because servers, on these
point of sale systems

00:25:05.650 --> 00:25:09.120
that they press in, they
don't enter the decimal point.

00:25:09.120 --> 00:25:11.570
Because it's faster to
just type in the numbers

00:25:11.570 --> 00:25:13.020
and enter two zeros.

00:25:13.020 --> 00:25:16.640
So his system required that
you enter a decimal point.

00:25:16.640 --> 00:25:19.090
And he realized, oh, gotta
change that behavior.

00:25:19.090 --> 00:25:21.560
So what can go wrong.

00:25:21.560 --> 00:25:23.600
We think about in
this hazard analysis,

00:25:23.600 --> 00:25:25.205
which is lots of things.

00:25:25.205 --> 00:25:26.830
And so when you're
designing something,

00:25:26.830 --> 00:25:29.350
you want to think of
what can go wrong.

00:25:29.350 --> 00:25:31.020
In software, we have bugs.

00:25:31.020 --> 00:25:34.165
Bugs can go wrong and we
try to mitigate for that.

00:25:34.165 --> 00:25:36.400
In physical design,
it can be unsafe.

00:25:36.400 --> 00:25:38.214
Someone's hand could
be caught something.

00:25:38.214 --> 00:25:39.380
They could pinch their hand.

00:25:39.380 --> 00:25:41.380
It could cause injury.

00:25:41.380 --> 00:25:43.522
From that, we do a
specifications phase to really

00:25:43.522 --> 00:25:44.230
sit down say, OK.

00:25:44.230 --> 00:25:45.580
What is required?

00:25:45.580 --> 00:25:47.500
What's required of
this design without

00:25:47.500 --> 00:25:52.790
any specific instructions
of how to design it?

00:25:52.790 --> 00:25:54.180
What's required?

00:25:54.180 --> 00:25:56.320
So in this phase,
we really sit down

00:25:56.320 --> 00:25:58.710
to figure out what
we need to do.

00:25:58.710 --> 00:26:02.380
But we haven't said
what to do yet.

00:26:02.380 --> 00:26:04.550
We go on to creative design.

00:26:04.550 --> 00:26:07.550
Who here knows
how to brainstorm?

00:26:07.550 --> 00:26:10.010
Who here does not know
how to brainstorm?

00:26:10.010 --> 00:26:10.510
OK.

00:26:10.510 --> 00:26:11.480
Brainstorming is
really important

00:26:11.480 --> 00:26:13.354
and we'll talk about
this a little bit later.

00:26:13.354 --> 00:26:15.244
How you brainstorm
is important as well.

00:26:15.244 --> 00:26:16.910
This is the part where
we begin to think

00:26:16.910 --> 00:26:19.950
about all the different
things that are possible.

00:26:19.950 --> 00:26:21.950
And if you're working
with a good team or people

00:26:21.950 --> 00:26:23.650
you like a lot, it's
easier to come up

00:26:23.650 --> 00:26:25.660
with really interesting ideas.

00:26:25.660 --> 00:26:29.040
They may be terrible ideas but
they may be very interesting.

00:26:29.040 --> 00:26:30.606
And that's OK.

00:26:30.606 --> 00:26:32.980
From there, we start narrowing
down to conceptual design.

00:26:32.980 --> 00:26:37.670
What are the potential
solutions that we can make?

00:26:37.670 --> 00:26:41.410
So we might have a few different
ones that look pretty good.

00:26:41.410 --> 00:26:43.106
But they may not work together.

00:26:43.106 --> 00:26:44.730
We might say look,
we go down one path,

00:26:44.730 --> 00:26:46.600
we can't go down the other path.

00:26:46.600 --> 00:26:48.207
They are mutually exclusive.

00:26:48.207 --> 00:26:49.790
Or if we try to do
both paths, they're

00:26:49.790 --> 00:26:52.460
very hard to do together.

00:26:52.460 --> 00:26:54.800
So we narrow down
the concepts and then

00:26:54.800 --> 00:26:57.000
we say, OK, we're going
to pick something.

00:26:57.000 --> 00:26:59.060
At this phase, you
might just say,

00:26:59.060 --> 00:27:01.130
let's pick whatever
one we want to.

00:27:01.130 --> 00:27:05.030
Or you might have a process
for picking a design.

00:27:05.030 --> 00:27:06.960
You might ask
experts to help you

00:27:06.960 --> 00:27:09.260
pick which approach to take.

00:27:09.260 --> 00:27:10.540
You might do market research.

00:27:10.540 --> 00:27:12.289
You might do a whole
bunch of other things

00:27:12.289 --> 00:27:16.000
to figure out which
one you prototype.

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:19.360
And lastly, the last
step is verification.

00:27:19.360 --> 00:27:20.880
And I don't mean
quality assurance.

00:27:20.880 --> 00:27:23.340
I don't mean does it work
to the specification.

00:27:23.340 --> 00:27:27.080
Of course we expect it to
work as we want it to work.

00:27:27.080 --> 00:27:28.240
But I mean, do people like?

00:27:28.240 --> 00:27:28.980
Can they use it?

00:27:28.980 --> 00:27:30.470
Do they want to use it?

00:27:30.470 --> 00:27:32.797
Is it emotionally and
intellectually compelling?

00:27:32.797 --> 00:27:33.630
Does it makes sense?

00:27:33.630 --> 00:27:36.590
Does it connect with
people on these two levels?

00:27:36.590 --> 00:27:38.800
And that goes right down
to very small things.

00:27:38.800 --> 00:27:42.006
To parts and cars.

00:27:42.006 --> 00:27:44.380
Goes to things that are consumer
products and things that

00:27:44.380 --> 00:27:46.850
are less obvious in terms
of being consumer products.

00:27:50.580 --> 00:27:56.580
And we have an end solution but
is it an end solution, really?

00:27:56.580 --> 00:28:00.470
What solutions or products
do you know that cannot be

00:28:00.470 --> 00:28:01.630
improved upon?

00:28:01.630 --> 00:28:02.210
Any ideas?

00:28:06.200 --> 00:28:07.100
That's pretty good.

00:28:07.100 --> 00:28:08.120
Maybe there is
something out there.

00:28:08.120 --> 00:28:10.550
But I like the idea that
we can improve on anything.

00:28:10.550 --> 00:28:14.120
So end solutions mean if there's
more room for improvement,

00:28:14.120 --> 00:28:17.480
we go back and do the whole
process all over again.

00:28:17.480 --> 00:28:19.215
Let's map this to
cooking dinner.

00:28:19.215 --> 00:28:22.390
Who here has cooked dinner?

00:28:22.390 --> 00:28:25.586
Who has never cooked
anything in their life?

00:28:25.586 --> 00:28:28.200
Ah, it's worth cooking.

00:28:28.200 --> 00:28:28.700
You'll like.

00:28:28.700 --> 00:28:29.920
It will make you less hungry.

00:28:29.920 --> 00:28:32.934
So let's start off.

00:28:32.934 --> 00:28:34.350
We're going to
identify the needs.

00:28:34.350 --> 00:28:37.695
What is the underlying
reason that we cook dinner?

00:28:37.695 --> 00:28:38.844
AUDIENCE: Hunger.

00:28:38.844 --> 00:28:39.760
BLADE KOTELLY: Hunger.

00:28:39.760 --> 00:28:41.032
Because we're hungry.

00:28:41.032 --> 00:28:42.740
What other underlying
reasons could there

00:28:42.740 --> 00:28:43.984
be for cooking dinner?

00:28:43.984 --> 00:28:45.400
AUDIENCE: Other
people are hungry.

00:28:45.400 --> 00:28:47.299
BLADE KOTELLY: Other
people are hungry, yes.

00:28:47.299 --> 00:28:48.840
AUDIENCE: Could be
a social occasion.

00:28:48.840 --> 00:28:49.920
BLADE KOTELLY: A
social occasion.

00:28:49.920 --> 00:28:51.070
AUDIENCE: To stay alive.

00:28:51.070 --> 00:28:53.710
BLADE KOTELLY: To
stay alive, yes.

00:28:53.710 --> 00:28:56.448
Maslow's hierarchy here.

00:28:56.448 --> 00:28:59.304
AUDIENCE: Not to
take the dining plan.

00:29:02.160 --> 00:29:04.210
BLADE KOTELLY: To avoid
a required dining plan,

00:29:04.210 --> 00:29:04.970
you need to cook.

00:29:04.970 --> 00:29:05.280
OK.

00:29:05.280 --> 00:29:05.779
What else?

00:29:05.779 --> 00:29:08.720
AUDIENCE: To win or earn money.

00:29:08.720 --> 00:29:10.620
BLADE KOTELLY: To
win or earn money.

00:29:10.620 --> 00:29:12.750
Do you mean, on a TV show?

00:29:12.750 --> 00:29:13.925
Fantastic.

00:29:13.925 --> 00:29:15.260
AUDIENCE: I like cooking.

00:29:15.260 --> 00:29:16.010
BLADE KOTELLY: You like cooking.

00:29:16.010 --> 00:29:16.855
It's an enjoyable experience.

00:29:16.855 --> 00:29:17.647
It's fun to do.

00:29:17.647 --> 00:29:18.230
It's creative.

00:29:18.230 --> 00:29:18.710
What else?

00:29:18.710 --> 00:29:19.440
AUDIENCE: Boredom.

00:29:19.440 --> 00:29:20.290
BLADE KOTELLY: Boredom.

00:29:20.290 --> 00:29:20.860
I'm bored.

00:29:20.860 --> 00:29:21.590
What should I do?

00:29:21.590 --> 00:29:22.250
Watch TV?

00:29:22.250 --> 00:29:22.570
No.

00:29:22.570 --> 00:29:23.270
Play video games?

00:29:23.270 --> 00:29:23.660
No.

00:29:23.660 --> 00:29:24.160
Cook?

00:29:24.160 --> 00:29:26.200
Great.

00:29:26.200 --> 00:29:28.970
Why else would we cook?

00:29:28.970 --> 00:29:31.460
AUDIENCE: To come
up with new dishes.

00:29:31.460 --> 00:29:33.210
BLADE KOTELLY: To come
up with new dishes.

00:29:33.210 --> 00:29:34.584
To create, to
innovate on dishes.

00:29:34.584 --> 00:29:36.182
What else?

00:29:36.182 --> 00:29:37.390
AUDIENCE: To impress someone.

00:29:37.390 --> 00:29:38.806
BLADE KOTELLY: To
impress someone.

00:29:38.806 --> 00:29:40.084
Who might you want to impress?

00:29:40.084 --> 00:29:41.500
AUDIENCE: Boyfriend
or girlfriend.

